{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585655"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:15:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:15:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14996"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14996"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.13,0,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66725"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7684"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52178"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8114"},{"type":"tags","id":"9951"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18778"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66725"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EC1 inhibitor is a regulatory protein that controls both the complement cascade and the contact (kallikrein-kinin) system. Deficiency of this protein causes hereditary angioedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of C1 inhibitor deficiency?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uncontrolled activation of complement and contact systems","Decreased activation of complement proteins","Reduced bradykinin production","Enhanced complement regulation","Decreased vascular permeability"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn C1 inhibitor deficiency, there is \u003Cstrong\u003Euncontrolled activation of complement and contact systems\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because C1 inhibitor normally prevents spontaneous activation of these pathways. Without this regulation, there is excessive complement activation and increased bradykinin production, leading to angioedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased activation of complement proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - C1 inhibitor deficiency actually leads to increased complement activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced bradykinin production\u003C/strong\u003E - Bradykinin levels increase due to lack of regulation of the contact system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced complement regulation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of what occurs in C1 inhibitor deficiency\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased vascular permeability\u003C/strong\u003E - Increased bradykinin leads to increased vascular permeability, causing tissue swelling\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical manifestation of C1 inhibitor deficiency is hereditary angioedema, characterised by recurrent episodes of swelling affecting various body parts including the airways, gastrointestinal tract, and extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["C1 inhibitor deficiency leads to uncontrolled activation of complement and contact systems, causing angioedema","C1 inhibitor normally prevents spontaneous activation of C1 and regulates the contact (kallikrein-kinin) system","Hereditary angioedema is caused by C1 inhibitor deficiency and presents with recurrent episodes of swelling"],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kerrigan MJ, Naik P. C1 Esterase Inhibitor Deficiency. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538166/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52178"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14996"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52178"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T20:30:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:31:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7684"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66725"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship